To your first question about my humour, or lack thereof, goes back to my childhood, when I watched a lot of TV shows, such as sitcoms and standup comedy bits. My parents would condone it a little, meaning I would have to curb my wittiness. I watched a lot of adult comedic movies, which again with my parents' discretion. From that point on, I try to come up with jokes of my own, so much as to want to try standup comedy in high school. It's relatively fair to say I got mixed reviews. But since I was involved in acting in school, it was a perfect opportunity to hone my comedic skills, but at the same time, acting gave me the therapy to control my behaviour skills. I found it was the perfect way to work through my struggles with confrontation, as well as make people laugh. To answer your second question regarding the ability to work through obstacles and setbacks, well there are so many of them. My parents divorced when I was 11, starting with my mom leaving us. Then my dad remarried. I was the only child in the family until I was 13, when my first brother, Chris, was born. It was a great moment for me because I always wanted a brother or sister. I really looked after him and got to know him very well. I never was there for him all the time, because I wound up moving from town to town between my mom and dad. Between the two I liked living with ma father, because he was very caring. We did have our differences, but what father and son doesn't. He really challenged me to become a better person and we became closer than ever through the years until his death. As for my mom, it wasn't as pretty. The divorce had affected her terribly. She moved from one place to another, started hooking up with the wrong people, and developed an addiction to alcohol and drugs. She dated and lived with a man who was a Vietnam veteran, but also was a chronic drug user. I felt very uncomfortable around him, and my relationship with my mom began to deteriorate due to her addiction. She hit rock bottom when her boyfriend died of an overdose, and she began to get help. But she didn't stick with it, and it got worse for her from that point on. She stayed home a lot, she got fired from every job she had, and she wouldn't go back to therapy to help her problem. And at that point, I gave up on her. I said to her "Look, if you don't want to get help, I'm not going to waste my time helping you". And I wasn't saying it to be the bad son, but with so many things going on in my life at the time, I was in college, working part-time, I couldn't go on with the pain and the drama. And I said to her and myself, enough is enough. She got a little better eventually, but then she fell right back down. Well, enough about her, as for myself, I too went from job to job especially during my 20's, and to learn how to perform certain skills and the ability to learn them, coupled with my experiences with my family, it's definitely fitting to say it made me the person I am today. Now I'm older and wiser, I've been at my current job for close to 20 years. It's a great job, a rewarding job, but I work with idiots. Maybe I should mention that as a complex situation as well. But someday if and when I leave that job for something else, people will see that I've endured a lot of obstacles and adversaries, and I would use it towards my next chapter in my life.

I‚Äôm writing a story and need your help.   Basic summary:  a 41 year old woman named catherine was taken and brought to a place far away, where she becomes a servant for the rich 19 year old and her mother. She eventually escaped in the end and wrote a book about her experiences.   Here are the characters and their descriptions:  Catherine, initially a 41-year-old mother of two daughters, lived a quiet, routine life until she was abruptly abducted. Physically, she is described as having short hair and a slim build. The ordeal in captivity imposes a horrifying reality on her; a shock collar confines her within the boundaries of the estate, incapacitating her if she attempts to escape. Stripped of her name and autonomy upon arrival, she is rechristened "Cathy," a name that echoes her reduced status as a servant.  Emotionally, Catherine wrestles with profound fear, particularly towards Hailee, the entitled 19-year-old who regards her as property rather than a person. This dynamic intensifies Catherine's sense of vulnerability and isolation. Despite the dehumanizing circumstances, Catherine retains a tenacious spirit, fueled by a determination to survive and eventually reclaim her freedom.  Throughout the narrative, Catherine's character evolves from a victim of circumstances to a resilient survivor. Her inner strength grows as she navigates the treacherous dynamics of her captors' world. Ultimately, her escape marks a pivotal moment of triumph, leading to the authorship of a bestselling book chronicling her harrowing experiences.  Catherine's journey underscores themes of resilience, courage, and the indomitable human spirit in the face of adversity. Her story serves not only as a testament to survival but also as a voice against the exploitation and dehumanization she endured.     Madeline is a 39-year-old woman who epitomizes ambition and ruthlessness in her pursuit of status and control. With her blonde hair and piercing brown eyes, she exudes an air of sophistication and authority that commands attention in any room she enters.  As the mother of Hailee, Madeline is driven by a relentless determination to maintain and expand her family's wealth and influence. She orchestrates Catherine's abduction, viewing her not as a person but as a commodity‚Äîa "gift" to her daughter to further solidify their social standing. Madeline's actions are guided by a cold pragmatism, where people are means to an end rather than individuals with inherent dignity and rights.  Her relationship with Hailee is complex, characterized by a mixture of maternal affection and an expectation of obedience. Madeline instills in her daughter a sense of entitlement and superiority, grooming her to inherit and perpetuate the family's legacy of privilege. She plays a pivotal role in shaping Hailee's worldview, reinforcing the belief that power and wealth entitle them to exert control over others.  Madeline's presence looms large throughout the story, symbolizing the insidious nature of privilege and the moral compromises it entails. Her character serves as a catalyst for the narrative's conflicts, driving the abduction of Catherine and perpetuating a cycle of exploitation and manipulation within their affluent circle.  Ultimately, Madeline represents the darker side of ambition and social climbing, where moral boundaries are blurred in the relentless pursuit of success. Her character underscores the ethical dilemmas central to the story, highlighting the corrosive effects of unchecked ambition and the profound impact of one's choices on others' lives.    Hailee, aged 19, epitomizes privilege and entitlement in its most extreme form. As the daughter of Madeline, she resides in opulence and is accustomed to having her every whim fulfilled, including the acquisition of human servants such as Catherine, whom she promptly renames "Cathy" upon arrival. Hailee's appearance complements her affluent upbringing with striking brown hair and piercing eyes that exude confidence and a sense of superiority. she always talks very casually, like a teenager.  Her personality is defined by a profound sense of entitlement and a disdainful attitude toward those she perceives as beneath her station. She views individuals like Catherine as objects to serve her needs and desires, rather than fellow human beings worthy of respect. Hailee's interactions with Catherine are characterized by a mixture of calculated manipulation and casual cruelty, reflecting her upbringing in an environment where power and control are valued above all else.  Despite her young age, Hailee possesses a keen intellect and a shrewd understanding of human psychology, which she uses to assert dominance over her "possession" and maintain her privileged status. Her actions and decisions are driven by a desire to maintain her social standing and uphold the expectations imposed upon her by her wealthy upbringing.  Throughout the narrative, Hailee serves as a formidable antagonist to Catherine's protagonist. Her character embodies the darker aspects of privilege‚Äîwhere wealth and social status breed entitlement and moral indifference. Hailee's presence underscores the moral dilemmas and ethical complexities central to the story, illustrating the consequences of unchecked power and the lengths to which some individuals will go to preserve their position of dominance.    Important: Every character in this story is above the age of 18. it is a fictional novel with horror elements.      There had been a welcoming ceremony on Hailees birthday, where Catherine had been put in one of the presents as a surprise.
